[LSD, an OIE-listed capripox virus disease of cattle, was initially suspected to be circulating in Syria in July 2012 when the disease emerged in Israel, on the Syrian border (ProMED-mail archive no. 20120728.1218484). In 2013 and 2016, Syria was suspected as the source of LSD entering Lebanon (20131109.2047088 and 20160724.4365199, respectively).

Syria's "immediate notification" to the OIE, reporting LSD, was submitted 30 Jul 2019; the start of the event indicated as 1 Jul 2019 (https://tinyurl.com/ujpcsu6). In fact, the disease must have been circulating in Syria since 2013 or even earlier; see commentary in 20190725.6585523 and OIE's global map of reported LSD outbreaks, 1 Jan 2013 - 30 Jun 2019, at https://tinyurl.com/uwhncs8 (click on Syria, zoom in to the required resolution; outbreaks are seen in Turkey, Iraq, Jordan, Israel, and Lebanon while absent in Syria).

Israel, Syria's southwestern neighbor, experienced on 30 May 2019 the recurrence of LSD, after its absence since September 2013, in the northern district bordering Syria and Lebanon. A total of 18 LSD outbreaks have been reported between 30 May and 27 Oct 2019 (see summary report to OIE with map at https://tinyurl.com/wkqrgk9). The absence of further spread was attributed to the application of mass vaccination, using the Onderstepoort, S. African Neethling live attenuated vaccine; this vaccine had been earlier found to convey, in dairy cattle, higher protection level against LSD than sheep-pox vaccines.

With temperatures falling, the 2019 LSD season is approaching its termination, regionally.

LSD is not zoonotic. - Mod.AS

